WEBVTT

00:16.980 --> 00:18.730
Rowan Fielding,
I'm your great aunt,

00:18.930 --> 00:21.080
Carlotta Mayfair.

00:21.280 --> 00:21.960
Is that my --

00:22.150 --> 00:23.430
Your mother.

00:23.630 --> 00:24.570
Millie: Where's the necklace?

00:24.770 --> 00:25.520
Carlotta:
I took it off Dierdre.

00:25.720 --> 00:26.740
What are you gonna do?

00:26.940 --> 00:28.610
The only thing worth trying.

00:28.810 --> 00:29.830
I'll find out who did this.

00:30.030 --> 00:32.310
I saw a guy stop the elevator
and get in with her.

00:32.510 --> 00:33.180
They're out looking for him.

00:33.380 --> 00:34.230
Rowan: Who is that?

00:34.430 --> 00:35.660
He's connected with your family.

00:35.860 --> 00:36.580
They call him Lasher.

00:36.780 --> 00:37.880
Now your time has come.

00:38.080 --> 00:39.230
The 13th witch.

00:39.430 --> 00:41.020
Rowan: I just felt like
I was swept away.

00:41.220 --> 00:42.110
That's why you need
to understand

00:42.310 --> 00:43.320
the full extent of your powers.

00:43.520 --> 00:45.140
I can help you with that.

00:48.100 --> 00:49.360
[goat bleats]

01:07.120 --> 01:09.730
[crying]

01:15.960 --> 01:18.400
<i>[ominous music]</i>

01:18.600 --> 01:21.930
<i>[chanting]</i>

01:22.130 --> 01:28.100
<i>♪ </i>

01:43.770 --> 01:47.120
[sobbing and wailing]

02:02.700 --> 02:05.320
[drums playing]

02:05.520 --> 02:12.400
♪

03:00.280 --> 03:03.370
[gasping]

03:06.810 --> 03:08.200
Rowan.

03:09.420 --> 03:12.210
<i>[haunting music]</i>

03:12.410 --> 03:19.210
<i>♪ </i>

03:40.620 --> 03:42.070
Hey.

03:42.270 --> 03:43.420
You sleep well?

03:43.620 --> 03:46.160
Yeah.

03:46.360 --> 03:48.640
Thank you.

03:48.840 --> 03:49.900
How about you?

03:50.100 --> 03:53.300
I had strange dreams.

03:53.500 --> 03:54.860
- <i>You?</i>
- Yeah.

03:55.060 --> 03:56.210
<i>Not surprising.</i>

03:56.410 --> 03:58.080
<i>We shared a lot last night.</i>

03:58.280 --> 03:59.560
I shared a lot.

03:59.760 --> 04:01.220
I overshared.

04:01.420 --> 04:04.260
- I know enough about you now
to know how rare that is.

04:04.460 --> 04:06.960
- And I still don't know
anything about you.

04:07.160 --> 04:10.520
I mean, who is Ciprien Grieve?

04:14.400 --> 04:18.100
He likes baseball, the Astros,

04:18.300 --> 04:22.280
and...

04:22.480 --> 04:23.800
duck hunting.
[blows lure]

04:28.020 --> 04:30.860
Thumbscrews?

04:31.060 --> 04:32.550
What is this thing?

04:32.750 --> 04:35.900
That is a maple syrup tap.

04:36.100 --> 04:37.820
It's a good memory.

04:38.020 --> 04:40.650
That's what they all are.

04:40.850 --> 04:42.350
- Yeah, you can go back
to the maple grove

04:42.550 --> 04:43.690
whenever you want.

04:43.890 --> 04:45.780
- I've never been there,
actually.

04:45.980 --> 04:48.310
Odette brought that back
for me from Vermont.

04:48.510 --> 04:50.830
- You don't have a maple grove
of your own?

04:51.030 --> 04:55.100
- Other people's memories
are... cleaner.

04:55.300 --> 04:57.830
Odette dropped that off
for you for the funeral.

05:00.310 --> 05:02.060
You're coming with me, right?

05:02.260 --> 05:04.980
Of course.

05:05.180 --> 05:06.330
We have a couple of hours.

05:06.530 --> 05:09.720
I don't wanna think
about it yet.

05:09.920 --> 05:12.290
Oh, my gosh.

05:12.490 --> 05:13.770
I love poached eggs.

05:13.970 --> 05:16.330
- I know.
I was in your head, remember?

05:18.070 --> 05:19.820
[laughs] I'm just kidding.

05:20.020 --> 05:21.820
Everybody likes Eggs Sardou.

05:22.020 --> 05:23.730
[laughs]

05:23.930 --> 05:25.390
[laughs]

05:25.590 --> 05:27.650
[door creaking]

05:27.850 --> 05:30.050
[water dripping]

05:30.240 --> 05:33.700
[stairs creaking]

05:33.900 --> 05:36.310
<i>[eerie music]</i>

05:36.510 --> 05:40.190
[breathy sighing]

05:40.390 --> 05:47.180
<i>♪ </i>

06:29.180 --> 06:32.240
The necklace is gone.

06:32.440 --> 06:34.720
He's coming for her.

06:34.920 --> 06:40.110
<i>♪ </i>

06:40.980 --> 06:44.420
<i>[eerie music]</i>

06:44.620 --> 06:47.430
<i>[voices whispering</i>
<i>indistinctly]</i>

06:47.630 --> 06:50.130
<i>♪ </i>

06:50.320 --> 06:53.910
<i>[vocalizing]</i>

06:54.110 --> 07:00.780
<i>♪ </i>

07:18.450 --> 07:20.630
[genteel music playing]

07:20.830 --> 07:22.850
<i>- Amelia, tell Richard</i>
<i>we'll be ready to leave</i>

07:23.050 --> 07:23.980
<i>in 30 minutes.</i>

07:25.850 --> 07:27.340
Daddy, come on.

07:27.540 --> 07:29.030
We need to get there
before Carlotta does.

07:29.230 --> 07:32.340
- Josephine,
I am enjoying the news.

07:32.540 --> 07:35.000
I will not let my sister
ruin my morning.

07:35.200 --> 07:36.520
- You really want
Carlotta in charge

07:36.720 --> 07:38.960
of Rowan's first impression
of the family?

07:39.160 --> 07:40.920
- My sister carries
all the rope

07:41.110 --> 07:43.270
she needs to hang herself.

07:43.460 --> 07:44.880
Besides, Rowan seems
like a smart girl.

07:45.080 --> 07:46.050
She's a doctor, after all.

07:46.250 --> 07:48.880
She'll--she'll see what's what.

07:49.080 --> 07:51.840
Still, hurry up.

07:52.040 --> 07:53.880
[sighs]

07:54.080 --> 07:56.970
It's hard to hurry
on a day like today.

07:57.170 --> 08:00.670
♪

08:00.870 --> 08:04.330
I certainly hope they catch
whoever killed her.

08:04.530 --> 08:08.800
- Whether they catch him
or not, he will be punished.

08:11.850 --> 08:12.990
You've seen it?

08:13.190 --> 08:16.120
<i>[mysterious music]</i>

08:16.320 --> 08:19.130
[screaming]

08:19.330 --> 08:23.700
Get it off me! Please! Ah!

08:23.900 --> 08:25.570
- [car horn honks]
<i>- Asshole!</i>

08:25.770 --> 08:26.740
Help me.

08:26.940 --> 08:27.920
Please, help.

08:28.120 --> 08:29.220
Please, help me.

08:35.400 --> 08:36.840
- No, no, no, no, no, no.
- Calm down.

08:37.040 --> 08:37.930
- Listen, listen.
- No, no.

08:38.130 --> 08:39.410
[gibberish]

08:39.610 --> 08:40.800
<i>- What is he talking about?</i>
- [screams]

08:41.000 --> 08:42.410
<i>[blood whooshing]</i>

08:42.610 --> 08:45.410
<i>[spacey music]</i>

08:45.610 --> 08:47.940
<i>♪ </i>

08:48.140 --> 08:51.510
<i>[heart beating]</i>

08:51.710 --> 08:53.810
I think we should get going.

08:54.010 --> 08:56.030
I had it.

08:56.230 --> 08:57.080
What did you see?

08:57.280 --> 08:59.210
Its heart, its veins.

08:59.410 --> 09:01.130
It was beautiful.

09:01.330 --> 09:03.550
I just need to keep practicing.

09:07.340 --> 09:08.730
We should get going.

09:11.950 --> 09:14.840
I'll be with you
the whole time.

09:15.030 --> 09:17.660
Don't worry.

09:17.860 --> 09:19.740
- It's a strange way to meet
my family, that's all.

09:22.360 --> 09:24.020
- Shall we?
- Yeah.

09:24.220 --> 09:25.750
Let me just grab my purse.

09:29.410 --> 09:33.290
Okay.

09:33.490 --> 09:36.250
[organ music]

09:36.450 --> 09:43.290
♪

10:03.830 --> 10:06.710
There you go.

10:06.910 --> 10:08.630
Pretty as a peach.

10:08.830 --> 10:15.710
♪

10:22.980 --> 10:24.990
That's Barnaby Mayfair.

10:25.190 --> 10:28.740
He married a Kennedy
a couple years ago.

10:28.930 --> 10:31.650
That's Electa Mayfair,
the older woman there.

10:31.850 --> 10:35.660
People say she's been alive
since the Civil War.

10:35.850 --> 10:38.830
- You wanna sit in the back?
- Mm-hmm.

10:39.030 --> 10:41.310
Um, um, I should go pay
my respects.

10:41.510 --> 10:43.920
- Okay.
- Thank you.

10:44.120 --> 10:44.930
I'll see you soon.

10:45.120 --> 10:46.320
All right.

10:46.520 --> 10:53.320
♪

10:53.520 --> 10:56.680
- Is that--is that her?

10:56.880 --> 10:59.110
[congregation chattering]

10:59.310 --> 11:02.030
Oh, my gosh.

11:02.230 --> 11:06.380
I don't think that's her.

11:06.580 --> 11:08.210
Hello, my dear.

11:08.410 --> 11:09.730
I'm so glad you came.

11:09.930 --> 11:11.870
- Of course.
- Please, come to the front.

11:12.060 --> 11:13.780
Okay.

11:13.980 --> 11:16.090
- She's getting
her claws in quickly.

11:16.290 --> 11:18.740
- I hear she's having
a gathering afterwards.

11:18.940 --> 11:20.480
No family invited.

11:20.680 --> 11:21.530
Hmm.

11:21.730 --> 11:27.270
♪

11:27.470 --> 11:29.710
- We now call forward
the immediate family.

11:29.910 --> 11:36.710
♪

11:43.540 --> 11:46.380
<i>[otherworldly singing]</i>

11:46.580 --> 11:53.420
<i>♪ </i>

12:06.870 --> 12:08.010
[phone buzzes]

12:08.210 --> 12:09.710
Sorry.

12:09.910 --> 12:11.270
I need to take this.

12:11.470 --> 12:14.190
Okay.

12:14.390 --> 12:15.930
Hello?

12:16.130 --> 12:20.980
<i>♪ </i>

12:21.180 --> 12:22.890
That was my boss.

12:23.090 --> 12:26.030
They think they got
the guy from the elevator.

12:26.230 --> 12:28.290
I'm sorry, but they need me
over there right now.

12:28.490 --> 12:29.990
I'll drop you off
at my place and loop back.

12:30.190 --> 12:31.860
- No, no, no.
You go.

12:32.060 --> 12:35.380
I--I wanna stay to the end
just to see her, you know,

12:35.580 --> 12:36.990
put to rest.

12:37.190 --> 12:38.470
- I don't know.
Are you sure?

12:38.670 --> 12:40.560
- Yeah.
It's broad daylight.

12:40.760 --> 12:44.260
You go, and I'll take
a cab back to your place.

12:44.460 --> 12:45.960
Keep your phone on, okay?

12:46.160 --> 12:47.610
- Call me if you need me.
- I'll be fine.

12:47.810 --> 12:54.650
<i>♪ </i>

13:05.670 --> 13:08.460
<i>[eerie music]</i>

13:08.660 --> 13:15.500
<i>♪ </i>

13:26.080 --> 13:30.660
<i>- I'm sure it's upsetting</i>
<i>to see that.</i>

13:30.860 --> 13:31.740
- No wonder
everyone was looking

13:31.940 --> 13:33.570
at me like I'm a ghost.

13:33.770 --> 13:37.100
- They're looking at you
like you're a miracle.

13:37.300 --> 13:39.010
- Someone knew I was alive,
but said I was dead.

13:39.210 --> 13:40.880
Why?

13:41.080 --> 13:44.760
- I'm sure you have
so many questions.

13:44.960 --> 13:47.500
And I don't want to leave
them unanswered.

13:47.700 --> 13:48.940
But I must get to the house.

13:49.130 --> 13:51.590
There's a small reception.

13:51.790 --> 13:52.900
Why don't you come?

13:53.100 --> 13:55.250
- I'm sorry.
I don't think I should.

13:55.450 --> 13:57.730
- You could see
where your mother lived.

13:57.930 --> 14:00.510
There are a few things
of hers that you should have.

14:00.710 --> 14:01.560
I'll think about it.

14:01.760 --> 14:02.860
Thank you.

14:03.060 --> 14:09.860
<i>♪ </i>

14:21.260 --> 14:23.060
[shutter snapping]

14:23.260 --> 14:30.050
<i>♪ </i>

14:56.990 --> 14:58.480
But they did send flowers,

14:58.680 --> 15:00.570
<i>so I suppose</i>
<i>they had the flowers covered.</i>

15:00.770 --> 15:02.100
How strange that was.

15:02.290 --> 15:04.400
<i>♪ </i>

15:04.600 --> 15:07.190
- Welcome.
You must be Dr. Fielding.

15:07.390 --> 15:10.360
- Yes.
- Please, come in.

15:10.560 --> 15:12.580
Your aunt will meet you
in the library.

15:12.780 --> 15:19.630
♪

15:40.910 --> 15:44.790
[wind blowing]

15:44.990 --> 15:50.970
<i>♪ </i>

15:51.170 --> 15:53.670
Sam said you had come.

15:53.870 --> 15:55.980
I'm so glad
you changed your mind.

15:56.170 --> 15:57.450
Please.

15:57.650 --> 16:01.850
Great.

16:02.050 --> 16:03.720
- I thought
you might want to see

16:03.920 --> 16:06.150
some photos of your mother.

16:14.250 --> 16:16.820
Was she a Mayfair?

16:17.020 --> 16:20.650
She was our cousin.

16:20.850 --> 16:25.000
I'm sorry I wasn't
at the funeral to say goodbye.

16:25.200 --> 16:29.270
But I'm even more sorry
for you, for your loss.

16:29.470 --> 16:31.100
You're mourning two mothers.

16:31.300 --> 16:34.930
And I just can't imagine it.

16:35.130 --> 16:37.360
Thank you.

16:37.560 --> 16:40.410
But all of these photos
and these memories,

16:40.610 --> 16:42.940
and she never said anything
about it to me.

16:43.130 --> 16:44.630
Oh, you must forgive her.

16:44.830 --> 16:47.420
It's my fault.
I swore her to secrecy.

16:47.620 --> 16:50.590
It was one of the conditions
of her taking you.

16:50.790 --> 16:51.680
But why?

16:51.880 --> 16:53.340
Things don't end well

16:53.540 --> 16:57.560
for the women in this family.

16:57.760 --> 16:59.340
So it was you.

16:59.540 --> 17:02.740
You told everyone I was dead?

17:02.940 --> 17:04.480
I'd do it again.

17:04.680 --> 17:06.260
Look at you.

17:06.460 --> 17:08.180
You're a doctor.

17:08.380 --> 17:14.010
You're a success
and so independent.

17:14.210 --> 17:16.060
Ellie gave you that.

17:16.250 --> 17:19.930
- But at the expense
of knowing who I really was,

17:20.130 --> 17:24.190
who I am.

17:24.390 --> 17:25.980
- If it'll make you feel
any better,

17:26.180 --> 17:29.160
it's what Deirdre
wanted for you too.

17:29.350 --> 17:32.460
I don't mean that she wasn't
devastated to lose you.

17:32.660 --> 17:35.510
Of course she was.

17:35.710 --> 17:40.210
But she wanted you free
from this family, free from...

17:40.410 --> 17:43.260
<i>[mysterious music]</i>

17:43.460 --> 17:47.130
It's all too much to explain.

17:47.330 --> 17:48.570
Free from him.

17:48.770 --> 17:51.310
<i>♪ </i>

17:51.510 --> 17:53.740
Good.

17:53.940 --> 17:56.270
Good.

17:56.470 --> 17:58.100
You understand.

17:58.300 --> 18:01.540
Now that you're here,
knowledge is what you need

18:01.730 --> 18:03.840
to protect yourself.

18:04.040 --> 18:08.320
There are some in this family
who will lie to you.

18:08.520 --> 18:11.590
They'll try to convince you
that he is a gift.

18:11.790 --> 18:14.460
<i>♪ </i>

18:14.660 --> 18:18.470
The devil comes in many forms.

18:18.660 --> 18:23.040
When I was eight years old,
he came to me

18:23.230 --> 18:25.390
and offered himself.

18:25.580 --> 18:28.040
I'd read enough scripture.

18:28.240 --> 18:32.350
I knew his true nature.

18:32.550 --> 18:34.700
So I rejected him.

18:34.900 --> 18:37.270
- You're saying
he can be rejected,

18:37.470 --> 18:39.570
that there's a choice?

18:39.770 --> 18:42.750
Deirdre wasn't as strong.

18:42.950 --> 18:45.540
But I'm sure you are.

18:45.740 --> 18:47.100
[doors open]

18:47.300 --> 18:49.020
<i>- Let the celebration</i>
<i>of life begin!</i>

18:49.220 --> 18:50.540
<i>Come on, everybody.</i>
<i>[people whooping]</i>

18:50.740 --> 18:52.500
<i>All right.</i>
<i>You can set up in there, guys.</i>

18:52.700 --> 18:53.850
Oh, Carl.

18:54.050 --> 18:54.850
There you are.

18:55.050 --> 18:58.200
[laughs softly]

18:58.400 --> 19:00.290
Thank you very much
for the invitation.

19:00.490 --> 19:03.120
And I am so very sorry
we're late.

19:03.320 --> 19:04.470
Well, you're here now.

19:04.670 --> 19:06.950
Mm.

19:07.150 --> 19:09.040
Why is everybody
looking so somber?

19:09.240 --> 19:11.300
My Deirdre was a beam of light.

19:11.500 --> 19:13.340
Can't we be a little joyous?

19:15.510 --> 19:18.180
[ragtime music playing
on phonograph]

19:18.380 --> 19:21.620
♪

19:21.810 --> 19:22.880
<i>Let's party, everyone!</i>

19:23.080 --> 19:24.230
[cheering]

19:24.430 --> 19:26.620
Please, Tessa,

19:26.820 --> 19:29.490
don't get up on your high horse
today and embarrass yourself.

19:29.690 --> 19:31.360
[sighs]

19:31.560 --> 19:33.320
♪

19:33.520 --> 19:36.240
[elevator bell dings]

19:36.440 --> 19:37.980
- Two of our guys
spotted him, grabbed him

19:38.180 --> 19:39.330
before he could hurt himself.

19:39.530 --> 19:41.030
- You sure
he's not just tweaking?

19:41.230 --> 19:42.420
No way.

19:42.620 --> 19:43.640
Albrecht's here.

19:43.840 --> 19:45.640
He wants to watch you work.

19:45.840 --> 19:47.290
Oh.

19:47.490 --> 19:51.780
Guess I chose a good day
to wear a suit.

19:51.980 --> 19:53.690
- <i>Jeez.</i>
- Samir.

19:53.890 --> 19:54.870
Ciprien.

19:55.070 --> 19:56.690
Sir, it's been a long time.

19:56.890 --> 19:59.480
Is there a file on him,
anything I should know?

19:59.680 --> 20:01.730
- I would prefer
that you read him cold.

20:03.910 --> 20:05.090
After you.

20:05.290 --> 20:08.220
<i>[grunting]</i>

20:14.140 --> 20:15.710
- Can you work with him
in this state?

20:15.910 --> 20:19.890
[strained groaning]

20:20.090 --> 20:22.280
Hey.

20:22.480 --> 20:24.550
It's all right.

20:24.750 --> 20:26.510
You're safe now.

20:26.710 --> 20:29.290
[straining] I'm so tired.

20:29.490 --> 20:31.470
Make it stop.

20:31.670 --> 20:33.770
- I'm gonna come
a little closer.

20:33.970 --> 20:35.080
I'm gonna put my hands on you.

20:35.280 --> 20:39.560
I promise you,
I won't hurt you.

20:39.760 --> 20:41.430
I just need to see
what you were up to yesterday.

20:41.630 --> 20:44.440
<i>♪ </i>

20:44.640 --> 20:46.870
It's okay. It's okay.

20:47.070 --> 20:49.660
[low whooshing sound]

20:49.860 --> 20:52.620
<i>[tense music]</i>

20:52.820 --> 20:56.140
<i>♪ </i>

20:59.050 --> 21:05.240
[straining]

21:05.440 --> 21:06.760
It was him.

21:06.960 --> 21:09.510
He was in the elevator
with her.

21:09.710 --> 21:11.940
- Used a garrote.
- Hmm.

21:12.140 --> 21:14.120
Was he in control
of his actions?

21:14.320 --> 21:16.630
Or was he being operated on
by an outside force?

21:18.940 --> 21:20.860
You mean, was he possessed?

21:21.060 --> 21:22.650
- Well, I try to avoid
that word when I can.

21:22.850 --> 21:24.350
Too many outdated associations.

21:24.550 --> 21:26.130
But yes, that's
what I'm asking.

21:26.330 --> 21:27.390
No.

21:27.590 --> 21:29.090
The killing looked
professional.

21:29.290 --> 21:31.480
He was hired to do it.

21:36.870 --> 21:39.140
- We need to get him help.
- No. No.

21:39.340 --> 21:41.410
No!

21:41.610 --> 21:43.240
Oh, please, please. Ah!

21:43.430 --> 21:44.800
[bones snap]

21:45.000 --> 21:48.070
<i>♪ </i>

21:48.270 --> 21:49.810
<i>[low whooshing sound]</i>

21:50.010 --> 21:56.850
<i>♪ </i>

22:02.680 --> 22:03.590
Lasher.

22:08.340 --> 22:11.480
- Well, now, hair just
like your mother's.

22:11.680 --> 22:13.310
Got her eyes too, didn't you?

22:13.510 --> 22:16.140
- You know, I just love
San Francisco.

22:16.340 --> 22:19.010
My honey took me
on a trip up there, 1998.

22:19.210 --> 22:20.880
If only we'd known
you're alive,

22:21.080 --> 22:23.410
we could have met.

22:23.610 --> 22:26.190
But she who shall not be named
made like you never existed.

22:26.390 --> 22:28.240
You know that, right?

22:28.440 --> 22:29.630
- Yes.
Yeah.

22:29.830 --> 22:30.720
She told me.

22:30.920 --> 22:32.680
She told you?

22:32.880 --> 22:34.810
- Hi.
I'm Tessa.

22:35.010 --> 22:36.030
I've been dying to meet you.

22:36.230 --> 22:37.900
- Hi.
- This family doesn't have

22:38.100 --> 22:41.640
many neurosurgeons who've won
awards and gone to Stanford.

22:41.840 --> 22:42.860
You know a lot about me.

22:43.060 --> 22:43.990
Yeah.

22:44.190 --> 22:44.950
You're Deirdre's daughter,

22:45.150 --> 22:46.340
so I looked you up.

22:46.540 --> 22:47.690
Tessa, I told you.

22:47.890 --> 22:49.130
Beware of my daughter.

22:49.330 --> 22:51.130
She's a real--
what do they call it?

22:51.330 --> 22:53.350
A social justice warrior.

22:53.550 --> 22:56.440
If she starts to talk your ear
off about these burned women,

22:56.640 --> 22:58.050
just walk away.

22:58.250 --> 22:59.830
- The burned women.
I actually read about that.

23:00.030 --> 23:03.270
Has that happened here?

23:03.470 --> 23:05.270
- You brought it up.
- [sighs]

23:05.470 --> 23:07.710
- Yeah.
There's a crowd online

23:07.910 --> 23:10.410
who are saying that the women
were burned for being like us.

23:10.610 --> 23:12.150
<i>They are not like us.</i>

23:12.350 --> 23:14.500
And you know that.

23:14.700 --> 23:17.680
- Anyway, the point is,
it's exciting for the family

23:17.880 --> 23:19.420
to have a designee
who might actually use

23:19.620 --> 23:20.680
her power to help people.

23:20.880 --> 23:21.990
- I'm sorry.
A what?

23:22.190 --> 23:23.200
- A designee.
<i>- All right.</i>

23:23.400 --> 23:25.080
That's enough.

23:25.280 --> 23:27.640
Let's let her breathe.

23:27.840 --> 23:29.650
Has anyone offered you a drink?

23:29.850 --> 23:31.130
Not yet.

23:31.320 --> 23:32.300
Thank you.

23:32.500 --> 23:33.560
Thank you.

23:33.760 --> 23:35.290
It's lovely chatting
with you ladies.

23:37.300 --> 23:39.530
Oh, great.

23:39.720 --> 23:42.530
Thank you.

23:42.730 --> 23:47.180
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

23:47.380 --> 23:51.540
I think I saw you last night
at the funeral procession.

23:51.740 --> 23:52.760
That's what it is.

23:52.960 --> 23:54.580
Yes.

23:54.780 --> 23:56.460
- Did you happen to notice
if I was with someone?

23:56.650 --> 23:57.540
No.

23:57.740 --> 23:59.370
Why?

23:59.570 --> 24:01.290
Just one of those nights.

24:01.490 --> 24:02.850
Hmm.

24:03.050 --> 24:06.250
- Um, hey that--that word
that Tessa used, "designee,"

24:06.450 --> 24:08.680
what does that mean?

24:08.880 --> 24:11.160
Come with me.

24:15.990 --> 24:17.690
The Mayfair Matriarchs.

24:17.890 --> 24:19.170
We call them the designees

24:19.370 --> 24:22.960
because the will
designates them.

24:23.160 --> 24:24.350
That's Mary Beth.

24:24.550 --> 24:26.700
She's my favorite.

24:26.900 --> 24:28.310
That's Antha.

24:28.510 --> 24:29.780
<i>She's your grandmother.</i>

24:31.090 --> 24:32.270
And that's Katherine.

24:32.470 --> 24:34.230
She built this house.

24:34.430 --> 24:35.450
Forgive me.

24:35.650 --> 24:37.320
<i>I'm not certain</i>
<i>about these two.</i>

24:37.520 --> 24:40.410
There are 12, after all.

24:40.610 --> 24:42.070
And Deborah.

24:42.270 --> 24:44.020
She's the furthest back
who had her portrait done.

24:44.220 --> 24:46.240
Sometime in the--

24:46.440 --> 24:49.190
I don't know exactly,
but it was way, way back.

24:50.410 --> 24:52.420
Deirdre should be here too.

24:52.620 --> 24:54.120
Of course,
Carlotta never let her

24:54.320 --> 24:56.300
have her portrait done.

24:56.500 --> 24:59.470
Probably never even told her
she owned the house.

24:59.670 --> 25:01.820
- Carlotta doesn't own
the house?

25:02.020 --> 25:03.220
Nope.

25:03.420 --> 25:05.440
She just wants you
to think she does.

25:05.640 --> 25:08.920
The designees are the ones
who are really in charge.

25:09.120 --> 25:10.390
That's you.

25:12.870 --> 25:15.880
Still, 300 years
of women handing down

25:16.080 --> 25:18.100
everything to their daughters.

25:18.300 --> 25:20.100
How many families can say that?

25:20.300 --> 25:21.930
Not many.

25:22.130 --> 25:24.890
- And when you have a daughter,
you'll give it all to her.

25:25.090 --> 25:25.940
Oh, no, no, no.

25:26.140 --> 25:27.200
No kids for me.

25:27.400 --> 25:29.330
My patients are my kids.

25:29.530 --> 25:31.680
If you say so.

25:31.880 --> 25:34.160
Anyway, you should talk
to my dad

25:34.360 --> 25:35.900
about your inheritance.

25:36.100 --> 25:41.860
He administers the trust.

25:42.060 --> 25:44.300
- They all seem to be wearing
the same necklace.

25:44.500 --> 25:47.170
It belongs to you now too.

25:47.370 --> 25:50.400
Where is it?

25:50.590 --> 25:51.960
- That's
a really good question.

25:52.160 --> 25:54.830
[ragtime music playing
on phonograph]

25:55.030 --> 26:01.880
♪

26:59.670 --> 27:01.900
- He was a hired hand,
like you said.

27:02.100 --> 27:04.510
In and out of jail,
nothing very interesting here.

27:04.710 --> 27:06.380
Thank you for your help
with this.

27:06.580 --> 27:08.770
- So Lasher killed him
for what he did to Deirdre?

27:10.030 --> 27:12.260
- I'm sorry you had to witness
the grisly epilogue.

27:12.460 --> 27:14.260
The thing is, sir,

27:14.460 --> 27:15.700
the elevator
at the Pontchartrain Hotel

27:15.900 --> 27:17.480
was wiped.

27:17.680 --> 27:19.140
Wiped?

27:19.340 --> 27:20.790
- I went over there
in the hours after the murder,

27:20.990 --> 27:22.660
and I couldn't get
a single memory.

27:22.860 --> 27:24.710
- Hmm.
- Somebody did some clean up.

27:24.910 --> 27:26.400
There is
a supernatural component

27:26.600 --> 27:27.970
to this that hasn't been
accounted for.

27:28.170 --> 27:30.020
- Hmm.
Well, that's very thorough

27:30.220 --> 27:31.710
of you, above and beyond.

27:31.910 --> 27:32.850
Thank you.

27:33.040 --> 27:34.460
I will keep it in mind.

27:34.650 --> 27:36.240
- Uh, don't you want me
to follow up on this?

27:36.440 --> 27:37.890
- You have to keep Ms. Fielding
safe while she's here.

27:38.090 --> 27:39.110
That's job enough.

27:39.310 --> 27:40.540
Thanks again for your help.

27:43.760 --> 27:45.160
[upbeat music playing]

27:45.360 --> 27:47.990
[Mayfairs chattering]

27:48.190 --> 27:55.000
♪

27:55.200 --> 27:58.000
[cell phone dings and buzzes]

27:58.200 --> 28:05.040
♪

28:19.880 --> 28:21.850
Oh.

28:22.050 --> 28:23.770
There's the guest of honor.

28:23.970 --> 28:26.190
You can call me
Uncle Cortland, if you like.

28:28.110 --> 28:29.770
- That's a very bad habit
you got there.

28:29.970 --> 28:32.210
- Oh, it's just
a little indulgence.

28:32.410 --> 28:34.170
This was my father's.

28:34.370 --> 28:35.780
His name was Julien.

28:35.980 --> 28:37.470
And we used to sit
together right in front

28:37.670 --> 28:38.820
of that fireplace in there

28:39.020 --> 28:40.520
with the family ledger
on his lap

28:40.720 --> 28:42.610
and this old thing
in his mouth.

28:42.810 --> 28:44.920
He'd say,
"Cortland, someday,

28:45.120 --> 28:47.570
you're gonna run this business.

28:47.770 --> 28:48.920
And I'll bet you good money,
you're

28:49.120 --> 28:50.840
gonna piss it all away."

28:51.040 --> 28:53.140
Looks like he was wrong.

28:53.340 --> 28:57.060
- Well, let's just say
my name's on the bank.

28:57.260 --> 29:00.500
[laughs]
And it's a good thing, too,

29:00.700 --> 29:02.940
because soon after he died,

29:03.130 --> 29:05.420
my sisters kicked me out
of this place.

29:05.620 --> 29:06.770
- You don't seem
like the kinda guy

29:06.960 --> 29:08.940
who gets pushed around.

29:09.140 --> 29:11.120
It was all they had.

29:11.320 --> 29:12.860
I'm a softie, really.

29:13.060 --> 29:14.510
Don't tell.

29:14.710 --> 29:17.070
Just look what they've done
with the place.

29:21.120 --> 29:25.610
Of course, the house belonged
to Deirdre legally,

29:25.810 --> 29:27.610
which means it's yours now
and everything in it,

29:27.810 --> 29:29.310
except for this pipe.

29:29.510 --> 29:30.440
I don't want it.

29:30.640 --> 29:31.620
What?

29:31.820 --> 29:33.310
The pipe or the house?

29:33.510 --> 29:36.060
Uh, don't be in a hurry
to decide.

29:36.250 --> 29:37.450
When you're ready,

29:37.650 --> 29:38.410
I'll help you
with the paperwork,

29:38.600 --> 29:40.410
no matter what you choose.

29:40.610 --> 29:42.320
I'm sure you're overwhelmed

29:42.520 --> 29:46.490
with such, uh, an abundance
of gifts.

29:50.760 --> 29:52.450
- They said
you would call him that.

29:55.410 --> 29:57.340
Are you frightened of him?

29:57.540 --> 29:59.860
Shouldn't I be?

30:00.060 --> 30:01.780
Absolutely not.

30:01.980 --> 30:04.210
He serves you,
not the other way around.

30:04.410 --> 30:06.780
Serves me how?

30:06.980 --> 30:09.570
What--what even is he?

30:09.770 --> 30:14.220
- Well, he is
an extension of yourself,

30:14.420 --> 30:18.580
something to connect you
to your mother and her mother

30:18.780 --> 30:19.880
and her mother before that.

30:20.080 --> 30:22.190
I don't know what that means.

30:22.390 --> 30:26.280
- Well, if you want
an explanation, ask him.

30:26.480 --> 30:28.370
Talk to him.

30:28.570 --> 30:29.890
<i>Here you are.</i>

30:30.090 --> 30:33.160
I have been a terrible hostess.

30:33.360 --> 30:35.640
I should've been
more attentive.

30:35.840 --> 30:37.860
I wanted to give you
a little something

30:38.060 --> 30:40.550
of your mother's, her rosary.

30:40.750 --> 30:41.820
Oh, no, no, no.

30:42.020 --> 30:44.300
I--I don't think
I should take that.

30:44.500 --> 30:45.990
Oh, please.

30:46.190 --> 30:48.480
Please, I want you to have it.

30:48.670 --> 30:50.350
It's for protection.

30:50.550 --> 30:52.520
- Oh, please,
don't scare her

30:52.720 --> 30:54.610
with your superstitious
nonsense.

30:54.810 --> 30:57.310
- I am the only one
looking out for her soul.

30:57.510 --> 30:59.880
- Oh, like you looked out
for Deirdre's?

31:00.080 --> 31:02.050
I did the best I could.

31:02.250 --> 31:04.880
- She kept your mother's light
under a bushel

31:05.080 --> 31:07.100
until she could snuff
it out entirely.

31:07.300 --> 31:09.370
How dare you?

31:09.570 --> 31:13.330
You weren't here day in
and day out, bathing her,

31:13.530 --> 31:17.160
feeding her, seeing to it
that she was still breathing.

31:17.360 --> 31:20.290
I have always had to do
the hard parts in this family

31:20.490 --> 31:23.550
while you played
the master of ceremonies.

31:23.750 --> 31:27.120
- Brava, sister dear.
[chuckles]

31:27.320 --> 31:29.690
After you held Deirdre
hostage for 30 years,

31:29.890 --> 31:32.300
you somehow made
yourself into the victim.

31:32.500 --> 31:34.650
<i>[tense music]</i>

31:34.850 --> 31:37.570
Your mother was very ill.

31:37.770 --> 31:40.750
I--I did what the doctors
told me.

31:40.940 --> 31:42.530
I'll show you
the medical records.

31:42.730 --> 31:44.620
And then you'll understand,
won't you?

31:44.820 --> 31:47.100
- Listen, maybe you should sit,
right here.

31:47.300 --> 31:50.150
<i>♪ </i>

31:50.350 --> 31:52.890
- Please, don't take pity
on her, sweetheart.

31:53.090 --> 31:54.190
Sweetheart?

31:54.390 --> 31:55.930
This woman is a doctor.

31:56.130 --> 31:58.110
You can refer to her as such.

31:58.310 --> 32:00.460
Josephine, it's time to go.

32:00.660 --> 32:01.980
Party's over.

32:02.180 --> 32:03.900
[crowd moans]

32:04.100 --> 32:05.810
Here, um...

32:06.010 --> 32:07.290
take my card.

32:07.490 --> 32:09.380
Please, find me in my office.

32:09.580 --> 32:11.170
When you're ready,

32:11.370 --> 32:14.820
we'll go over the will...
and everything else.

32:15.020 --> 32:20.090
<i>♪ </i>

32:20.290 --> 32:21.440
<i>Will you stay for dinner?</i>

32:21.640 --> 32:23.090
<i>♪ </i>

32:23.290 --> 32:25.350
You can have a look around.

32:25.550 --> 32:27.230
I'd like that.

32:27.430 --> 32:30.270
- Why are we leaving her there,
alone with Carlotta?

32:30.470 --> 32:32.450
- She's not alone
with Carlotta.

32:32.650 --> 32:34.570
And he doesn't need our help.

32:42.190 --> 32:43.760
Ciprien?

32:46.540 --> 32:49.470
Have you got out
the old Mayfair archives?

32:49.670 --> 32:50.730
Yes.

32:50.930 --> 32:53.560
The Haitian or the Dutch?

32:53.760 --> 32:55.600
The Dutch.

32:55.800 --> 32:58.000
- Now, what do you want
with that stuff,

32:58.200 --> 33:00.220
love letters and diaries?

33:00.420 --> 33:02.480
- If I'm going
to end all this,

33:02.680 --> 33:04.180
I need to know how it
all began.

33:04.380 --> 33:06.310
End it?

33:06.510 --> 33:09.620
Now, I know that's
not your job.

33:09.820 --> 33:13.000
- I'm assigned to protect
the Mayfairs, so it is.

33:16.010 --> 33:18.450
Don't get hurt.

33:18.650 --> 33:20.540
You're one of my favorites.

33:20.740 --> 33:23.540
<i>[eerie music]</i>

33:23.740 --> 33:30.630
<i>♪ </i>

33:36.630 --> 33:38.510
[gasps]

33:38.710 --> 33:40.210
<i>♪ </i>

33:40.410 --> 33:43.220
<i>[voices whispering</i>
<i>indistinctly]</i>

33:43.410 --> 33:50.170
<i>♪ </i>

33:54.350 --> 33:57.060
<i>[whispering voices growing]</i>

33:57.250 --> 34:04.050
<i>♪ </i>

34:17.460 --> 34:19.770
<i>[eerie laughter]</i>

34:19.970 --> 34:25.170
<i>♪ </i>

34:25.370 --> 34:28.090
[jazz music playing on TV]

34:28.290 --> 34:34.790
♪

34:34.990 --> 34:37.750
<i>[eerie music]</i>

34:37.950 --> 34:44.790
<i>♪ </i>

35:03.810 --> 35:07.130
[door creaking ominously]

35:07.320 --> 35:14.120
<i>♪ </i>

35:48.110 --> 35:49.340
[sighs]

35:49.540 --> 35:56.300
<i>♪ </i>

36:09.830 --> 36:12.490
- Dinner will be ready
momentarily.

36:12.690 --> 36:16.150
<i>♪ </i>

36:16.350 --> 36:19.280
- Thank you.
I'll be right down.

36:22.060 --> 36:23.710
[bell ringing]

36:25.020 --> 36:31.250
<i>♪ </i>

36:31.450 --> 36:33.210
- Gather the rest
of the staff in the kitchen.

36:33.410 --> 36:35.390
I've changed the dinner plans.

36:35.590 --> 36:38.340
<i>♪ </i>

36:44.470 --> 36:46.790
<i>- "She professes</i>
<i>her love for me,</i>

36:46.990 --> 36:50.010
<i>"but still,</i>
<i>she wears the necklace.</i>

36:50.210 --> 36:53.220
<i>So long as it hangs around</i>
<i>her neck, she belongs to him."</i>

36:56.270 --> 36:58.710
<i>[ominous music]</i>

36:58.910 --> 37:00.110
[cell phone buzzes]

37:00.310 --> 37:07.190
<i>♪ </i>

37:36.700 --> 37:39.440
- I heard about the portraits
and the designees today.

37:44.840 --> 37:48.630
Deirdre must've had
all her meals here.

37:48.830 --> 37:50.450
What was she like
when she was young?

37:52.930 --> 37:54.120
It seemed like she had
a little bit

37:54.320 --> 37:55.820
of a rebellious streak.

37:56.010 --> 37:58.300
[scoffs softly]

37:58.500 --> 38:02.260
<i>When did she get sick?</i>

38:02.460 --> 38:04.560
She was never really well.

38:04.760 --> 38:07.390
- What exactly
was her diagnosis?

38:07.590 --> 38:12.950
- Well, she had
so many... diagnoses.

38:15.260 --> 38:17.530
- I mean, I'd like to read
her medical file

38:17.730 --> 38:18.660
if you have it.

38:18.860 --> 38:20.670
[knock at door]

38:20.870 --> 38:22.450
- Would that be all,
Ms. Carlotta?

38:22.650 --> 38:23.970
Yes, Sam.

38:24.170 --> 38:25.450
- Very well.
Good night.

38:25.650 --> 38:27.450
Good night, Doctor.

38:34.450 --> 38:36.510
Eat, please.

38:36.710 --> 38:38.210
It's all for you.

38:38.400 --> 38:40.290
[laughs weakly]

38:43.720 --> 38:45.510
<i>I'll tell you the truth.</i>

38:47.680 --> 38:53.220
Your mother was the bane
of my existence.

38:53.420 --> 38:56.310
<i>From the moment she was born,</i>

38:56.510 --> 38:59.140
<i>she made every waking hour</i>

38:59.340 --> 39:02.270
of my life difficult.

39:02.470 --> 39:05.190
<i>And the hours I spent</i>

39:05.390 --> 39:07.710
praying for her, prayers

39:07.910 --> 39:10.540
better spent on the deserving.

39:10.740 --> 39:13.550
<i>[eerie music]</i>

39:13.740 --> 39:14.810
<i>♪ </i>

39:15.010 --> 39:16.590
This will be the last one.

39:16.790 --> 39:23.630
<i>♪ </i>

39:31.730 --> 39:35.610
I commend you, Deirdre,

39:35.810 --> 39:38.350
to almighty God.

39:38.550 --> 39:42.270
I entrust you to your creator.

39:42.470 --> 39:45.450
May you rest
in the arms of the Lord

39:45.650 --> 39:50.710
who formed you
from the dust of the Earth.

39:50.910 --> 39:55.940
May holy Mary, the angels,
and all of the saints

39:56.130 --> 40:00.070
welcome you
into the bosom of the Lord!

40:00.270 --> 40:07.070
<i>♪ </i>

40:24.690 --> 40:27.620
[cell phone buzzing]

40:27.820 --> 40:34.620
<i>♪ </i>

40:52.070 --> 40:54.520
For Stella,

40:54.720 --> 40:58.260
redeem her soul
from evil, oh, Lord.

40:58.460 --> 41:04.480
For Antha, redeem her soul
from evil, oh, Lord.

41:04.680 --> 41:10.440
For Deirdre, redeem her soul
from evil, oh, Lord.

41:10.640 --> 41:16.190
For Rowan, redeem her soul
from evil, oh, Lord!

41:16.390 --> 41:18.500
<i>♪ </i>

41:18.700 --> 41:19.500
What are you doing?

41:19.700 --> 41:25.370
<i>♪ </i>

41:25.570 --> 41:27.510
Help!
Help!

41:27.700 --> 41:28.550
<i>Get me out of here!</i>

41:28.750 --> 41:30.250
<i>Help!</i>

41:30.450 --> 41:32.160
<i>Someone, help me!</i>

41:32.360 --> 41:33.690
<i>Get me out of here!</i>

41:33.880 --> 41:34.860
<i>Rowan?</i>

41:35.060 --> 41:36.990
Sip, get me out of here, now.

41:37.190 --> 41:40.870
<i>♪ </i>

41:41.070 --> 41:42.560
Oh, Lord, forgive me my sins.

41:42.760 --> 41:44.040
<i>♪ </i>

41:44.240 --> 41:45.390
Rowan, it's me.

41:45.590 --> 41:47.830
[door rattling]

41:48.030 --> 41:49.920
<i>Hold on.</i>

41:50.120 --> 41:51.010
[flesh squelching]
Oh!

41:51.210 --> 41:52.830
[gasps]

41:53.030 --> 41:55.750
<i>♪ </i>

41:55.950 --> 41:56.840
- Sip.
No.

41:57.040 --> 41:58.670
No.

41:58.870 --> 42:00.930
Sip, stand up.
Don't pull it out.

42:01.130 --> 42:03.540
Don't pull it out.

42:03.740 --> 42:09.330
<i>♪ </i>

42:09.530 --> 42:12.200
[coughing]

42:12.400 --> 42:14.900
<i>♪ </i>

42:15.100 --> 42:16.030
She's already mine.

42:16.230 --> 42:19.170
<i>♪ </i>

42:19.360 --> 42:20.250
<i>[groans]</i>

42:20.450 --> 42:21.780
[grunting]

42:21.980 --> 42:24.740
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

42:24.940 --> 42:29.690
<i>♪ </i>

42:32.300 --> 42:35.570
♪

42:35.770 --> 42:36.840
No!

42:37.030 --> 42:38.580
What do you want from me?

42:38.780 --> 42:40.580
♪

42:40.780 --> 42:41.580
[ Gasps ]

42:41.780 --> 42:43.580
♪

42:43.780 --> 42:46.320
There's no happiness ahead
for you.

42:46.520 --> 42:47.890
You fell in love with her,
didn't you?

42:48.090 --> 42:51.980
♪

42:52.180 --> 42:54.640
Man: Mortal men are fragile.
There's never been one

42:54.840 --> 42:56.420
who can contend
with a Mayfair woman.

42:56.620 --> 43:01.590
♪

43:02.940 --> 43:08.210
♪

43:08.410 --> 43:11.300
Spalding: This episode is called
"Curiouser and Curiouser."

43:11.500 --> 43:14.480
Rowan is going down
this rabbit hole

43:14.680 --> 43:17.270
into the wonderland
of Mayfair --

43:17.470 --> 43:19.750
who they are, what they are,
how they work.

43:19.950 --> 43:21.450
[All crying]

43:21.640 --> 43:24.140
I think, deep down,
what she really wants

43:24.340 --> 43:27.100
is another encounter
with this being, Lasher,

43:27.300 --> 43:30.800
and she's gonna go to dangerous
places in order to have it.

43:31.000 --> 43:32.720
[Gasps]

43:32.920 --> 43:34.760
[Gasps, breathing heavily]

43:34.960 --> 43:41.030
♪

43:41.230 --> 43:42.470
Hey.

43:42.670 --> 43:44.340
Spalding:
It was really, really fun

43:44.540 --> 43:45.900
to work with
the production designer

43:46.100 --> 43:47.950
to think about what
the apartment would be like

43:48.150 --> 43:49.430
for this character.

43:49.630 --> 43:51.870
I still don't know
anything about you.

43:52.070 --> 43:55.780
I mean, who is
Ciprien Grieve?

43:55.980 --> 43:57.220
He wouldn't have, you know,

43:57.420 --> 43:59.310
his shelves crowded with
knickknacks or whatever.

43:59.510 --> 44:00.920
It's too much for him.

44:01.120 --> 44:02.570
He likes baseball?

44:02.770 --> 44:06.660
He wants to curate and choose
these few simple objects

44:06.860 --> 44:09.010
and to pick the memories
that he's gonna experience

44:09.210 --> 44:10.410
when he touches them.

44:10.610 --> 44:11.670
What is this thing?

44:11.870 --> 44:15.240
That is
a maple-syrup tap.

44:15.440 --> 44:16.590
It's a good memory.

44:16.790 --> 44:18.460
That's what they all are.

44:18.660 --> 44:19.890
Yeah. You can go back
to the maple grove

44:20.090 --> 44:21.240
whenever you want.

44:21.440 --> 44:23.460
I've never been there
actually.

44:23.660 --> 44:25.900
Odette brought that back
for me from Vermont.

44:26.100 --> 44:28.990
You don't have a maple grove
of your own?

44:29.190 --> 44:31.770
Other people's memories
are cleaner.

44:34.250 --> 44:35.520
[Indistinct conversations]

44:35.720 --> 44:37.990
[Gasps]

44:40.910 --> 44:43.180
[Doors bang open]

44:43.380 --> 44:46.050
[Mourners murmuring]

44:46.250 --> 44:49.050
Spalding: The rose petals are
really one of the ways

44:49.250 --> 44:51.270
that Lasher showed love
for Dierdre.

44:51.470 --> 44:54.230
It was a particular language
between the two of them.

44:54.430 --> 44:57.370
At the funeral, Lasher sends
these petals in,

44:57.570 --> 44:59.060
and it's the first moment

44:59.260 --> 45:02.850
that Rowan experiences Mayfair
magic as really beautiful.

45:03.050 --> 45:06.030
And Carlotta, who'll do
anything, as we've seen,

45:06.230 --> 45:09.340
to try to stop Lasher,
is furiously, even in death,

45:09.530 --> 45:12.030
trying to keep Lasher away
from Dierdre.

45:12.230 --> 45:16.780
♪

45:16.980 --> 45:21.480
Rowan has never had a family,
and now Rowan is being told

45:21.680 --> 45:23.000
she has this family,

45:23.200 --> 45:26.220
there are all of these
characters and relations.

45:26.420 --> 45:29.220
And I think she's very curious
to know them

45:29.420 --> 45:32.620
and curious to understand
who she is in relation to them,

45:32.820 --> 45:35.230
what they knew about
her mother, Dierdre.

45:35.430 --> 45:36.840
"Why was I sent away?"

45:37.040 --> 45:39.400
Carlotta: I'm sure
it's upsetting to see that.

45:41.050 --> 45:43.800
No wonder everyone's looking
at me like I'm a ghost.

45:44.000 --> 45:47.850
They're looking at you
like you're a miracle.

45:48.050 --> 45:50.720
Someone knew I was alive
but said I was dead. Why?

45:50.920 --> 45:52.640
We know the answer to that,

45:52.840 --> 45:55.940
but she's going to find out very
quickly that it was Carlotta.

45:57.550 --> 45:59.300
I thought you might want

45:59.500 --> 46:02.080
to see some photos
of your mother.

46:02.280 --> 46:06.040
Carlotta is very, very clever
in her approach to Rowan.

46:06.240 --> 46:08.440
She knows there's nothing to be
gained by lying.

46:08.640 --> 46:11.140
Rowan's gonna hear things from
other members of the family.

46:11.340 --> 46:13.050
She has to get out
in front of this.

46:13.250 --> 46:15.050
She wants to tell
her version of things.

46:15.250 --> 46:18.450
All of these photos
and these memories,

46:18.650 --> 46:20.320
and she never said anything
about it to me.

46:20.520 --> 46:23.150
You must forgive her.
It's my fault.

46:23.350 --> 46:24.850
I swore her to secrecy.

46:25.050 --> 46:27.020
So it was you?

46:27.220 --> 46:29.800
You told everyone
I was dead.

46:31.800 --> 46:34.160
If it'll make you feel
any better,

46:34.360 --> 46:36.730
it's what Dierdre wanted
for you, too.

46:36.930 --> 46:39.860
Being compassionate,
empathizing, you know, saying,

46:40.060 --> 46:43.210
"This is what Dierdre wanted
for you," which is a lie.

46:43.410 --> 46:46.300
You know, all those things are
real calculations by Carlotta,

46:46.500 --> 46:50.650
but they're true enough that
maybe Rowan will believe

46:50.850 --> 46:53.180
that's all that's bad about
what Carlotta's done.

46:53.380 --> 46:54.790
[Groaning]

46:54.990 --> 46:58.710
Cip knows that Lasher is
extraordinarily dangerous.

46:58.900 --> 47:00.350
Can you work with him
in this state?

47:02.870 --> 47:06.540
What he's learning in this is
that Lasher is tormented
by Dierdre's death.

47:06.740 --> 47:08.110
It's okay.

47:08.310 --> 47:09.540
[Groaning]

47:09.740 --> 47:12.110
Lasher has come
and is torturing this man

47:12.310 --> 47:13.810
for having killed Dierdre.

47:14.010 --> 47:15.590
Lasher is in grief,

47:15.790 --> 47:18.510
and that is information for Cip
and for the Talamasca.

47:18.710 --> 47:21.380
Lasher's clearly not responsible
for Dierdre's death.

47:21.580 --> 47:24.380
[Electricity crackles]

47:24.580 --> 47:26.170
Huh.

47:26.370 --> 47:35.180
♪

47:35.380 --> 47:37.270
Will that be all,
Miss Carlotta?

47:37.470 --> 47:38.790
Yes, Sam.

47:38.990 --> 47:42.580
Once those doors are shut
in that dining room,

47:42.770 --> 47:44.060
Carlotta can speak her truth.

47:44.250 --> 47:45.800
Those doors have been locked,

47:46.000 --> 47:48.150
and she can say what she wasn't
able to say before

47:48.350 --> 47:50.240
because she knows
how this is gonna end.

47:50.430 --> 47:51.890
I will tell you
the truth.

47:52.090 --> 47:56.110
Your mother was the bane
of my existence.

47:56.310 --> 47:58.590
Everything that Carlotta
has gambled on

47:58.790 --> 48:01.940
and tried to do in her life
to stop Lasher has not worked.

48:02.140 --> 48:04.380
Carlotta has been frustrated
every turn.

48:04.580 --> 48:07.820
This is the moment where she
thinks, "I have to do it now."

48:08.020 --> 48:11.910
Redeem her soul from evil,
oh, lord.

48:12.110 --> 48:16.440
Redeem her soul from evil,
oh, lord!

48:16.630 --> 48:17.920
For Rowan!

48:18.110 --> 48:22.570
Redeem her soul from evil,
oh, lord!

48:22.770 --> 48:24.790
"I'm close to the end
of my life,

48:24.990 --> 48:27.710
and so I'm going to do this
to the both of us

48:27.910 --> 48:30.280
and I believe this family
will be purged

48:30.470 --> 48:32.190
and rid of this being, Lasher."

48:32.390 --> 48:34.890
Help! Help!
Get me out of here!

48:35.090 --> 48:39.070
Carlotta's willing to take
herself down, the house down

48:39.270 --> 48:42.590
to destroy Rowan in pursuit
of making sure

48:42.790 --> 48:47.290
that Lasher's connection to
anyone on Earth is extinguished.

48:47.490 --> 48:48.900
Rowan! It's me!

48:49.100 --> 48:50.380
[Doorknob rattling]

48:50.580 --> 48:52.290
Hold on!

48:53.420 --> 48:54.640
[Knife plunges]

48:57.160 --> 48:59.650
No!

48:59.850 --> 49:01.730
Stand up.
Don't pull it out.

49:03.340 --> 49:05.260
Don't pull it out.

49:07.560 --> 49:09.100
She's already mine.

49:09.300 --> 49:16.620
♪

49:22.010 --> 49:24.810
<i>[eerie music]</i>

49:25.010 --> 49:31.850
<i>♪ </i>
